review_blob: Bottle, 50cl. Clear, deep amber color with a creamy beige head leaving some lacing. Sweet and roasted aroma of caramel, a hint of citrus fruits and floral hops. Full bodied with medium carbonation. Sweet flavor, lots of caramel malt, some citrus and a decent amount of bitterness. Long lasting, bitter aftertaste of nuts and some chocolate. A nice, warm brew. Its rich and complex, despite the abv.

Bottle, 50cl. Clear, amber with a long lasting, creamy beige head, leaving some lacing. Caramel malt, some citrusy hops and toffee in the aroma. Malty and sweet flavor of caramel, some orange and dark fruits with some slightly peppery notes, ending in a long lasting bitter aftertaste. Medium mouthfeel, crispy carbonation. A fine example of a simple, yet interesting brew. It has many layers, you can find some pretty nice things if you dig out all of them!

Bottle, 50cl. Pours sparkling, clear, pale golden with a small white head. Citrusy hoppy, fresh aroma. Medium carbonation, with a slightly watery mouthfeel. Toffeeish malty flavor with some citrus, lots of bitterness. Long lasting bitter aftertaste. All in all a nice ale, definitely worth a try for a hophead - nothing extreme, but better than average.

Bottle @ Mallaskukko, Turku, Finland. Pours pitch black with a long lasting light brown head and pretty lacing. Roasted aroma of chocolate, coffee and liquorice, maybe some vanilla. Full mouthfeel with medium carbonation. Coffee, lots of dark chocolate, some liquorice and roasted malt in the flavor. Overall this imperial stout is fine; full and complex. Everything you want from an imperial stout.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: Bottle, 50cl. Opaque black, high carbonation can be witnessed while pouring; quite tall dark tan head, which settles quite fast, leaving no head or lacing at all. Roasted, malty aroma of coffee and some chocolate. Medium bodied with lots of carbonation, could almost be described as fizzy. Flavor of dark chocolate and strong coffee, some licorice. A very balanced brew, although Id have given a higher rating if it wasnt as carbonated as it is now. My image of a *stout is a lot smoother than this.

Bottle, 33cl. Amber pour with very little head. Sweet aroma with notes of lightly roasted malt. A pleasant, malty, slightly roasted flavour with the right amount of sweetness. Medium bodied with low, but crispy carbonation. All in all this brew was a good surprise!

Poured in a snifter; black with a small tan head. Minimal aroma of coffee, roasted malt and liquorice. Medium bodied with generous carbonation. Salty, burnt, bitter and dry, with notes of salty liquorice, a long, burnt and dry aftertaste lingers. A complex combination of different dark flavours with the bitterness and ... viscosity (heh-heh).

Bottle. Deep brown, almost opaque with a generous tan head, leaving nice lacing. Roasted aroma of coffee and liquorice. Slightly watery mouthfeel, with medium carbonation. Roasted aroma with plenty of coffee, liquorice and some oak and caramel, with a long, burnt aftertase. A very balanced brew, but still missing the something that would make it top-notch!

0,33l Bottle. Clear, amber color with a small, but long lasting head with some lacing. A sweet and malty aroma of rum, oak, toffee and vanilla. A strong, malty vanilla flavour with notes of coconut and an oaky, wooden aftertaste. Medium mouthfeel with medium carbonation. I liked the original I&G; when I first had it, so this was a real treat for me! Nice!

Bottle, 50cl. Pours black, with a generous and long lasting head. Very subtle aroma of roasted malt with notes of caramel and chocolate. Medium bodied with low to medium carbonation, cant decide yet.. Its somewhere there in the middle. Sweet and roasted flavour with some chocolate, caramel. Pretty nice with strong flavoured cheese.

Bottle. Opaque black, with very little head. Roasted malty aroma with some liquorice and notes of coffee. Sweet and malty taste with ashy and burnt notes of malt, ashy finish with some bitterness. Medium bodied, with little carbonation.

Bottle, batch 327. Opaque black with a quickly diminishing tan head. Intense roasted maltyness and some liquorice in the aroma. Strong taste of roasted malt, liquorice and coffee, no taste of alcohol, ends in an intensely roasted, bitter and burnt taste. A long and roasted aftertaste. Not the most complex brew, but greatly balanced and tasty! As someone said before - like drinking delicious oil.

Opaque black with a generous tan head. A strong aroma of coffee, roasted malt and chocolate. Medium bodied, slightly oil-like feel - and look, hehe - to it. Roasted malt, dark chocolate, coffee and liquorice appear in the taste. A pleasant porter - tried it with cheese as they advised, sgood!

Bottle, 33cl. Light amber color, with a generous cloudy white head. Very fresh floral aroma with huge amounts of Cascade pushing through - a big hype for the flavor. Im sad to say the flavor itself doesnt reach the expectations the aroma lifted, but dont get me wrong, its not bad. A very hoppy flavor with caramel malt, pretty standard. Medium bodied, with little carbonation, slightly on the watery side, a definite summer-brew.

Bottle, 50cl. Pours deep red/brown with a nice, very slowly diminishing tan head. Sweet aroma of malt, fruity with notes of caramel and goldings. Medium bodied, with a roasty taste of caramel malt and dark fruits, leaving a long lasting, sweet and bitter aftertaste. Medium bodied, with little carbonation.

Bottle, 75cl, corked. Beautiful dark brown pour, against light it becomes more red than brown. Very little head. A sweetish malty aroma with notes of coriander, yeast, fruits, dark chocolate. Full mouthfeel with lots of carbonation. -A sweet taste of roasted malt, apricot, ash, licorice and chocolate. Interestingly the metal packaging my bottle came in says that the beer has 8% alcohol, but the label on the bottle says 7,5% !

Pours beautifully; deep red and copper with a small head. A nice malty, sweet, hoppy and citrusy aroma. First it hits you with an oily, sweet and full mouthfeel with a floral and hoppy taste with lots of caramel malt and bittering hops. Despite the high ABV you cant taste it at all, if not for the warm fuzzy feeling inside. Ends with a long, bitter finish.

Bottle. Light golden pour with little head and lacing. Very hoppy, grassy and floral aroma with notes of citrus fruits and spices. Medium bodied, with plenty of carbonation and bitterness. Grassy, floral, citrus and caramel malt flavor with decent hopping and a long lasting aftertaste.
UPDATED: MAR 14, 2008

Bottle, 50cl. Hazy golden yellow, with a white head. Fruity and sweet aroma with notes of yeast, wheat, banana and esters. A soft, medium bodied and highly carbonated mouthfeel with a citrusy taste with notes of banana, yeast and wheat. A decent  hefeweizen, but could use something more to make it unique.

Bottle, 75cl. Clear red brown with a medium white head. Fresh aroma with notes of citrus fruits, especially orange, coriander and cinnamon. A clean and light - almost watery - mouthfeel with some carbonation. Caramel malt, orange marmelade, toffee and orange peel in the the flavor. A decent bire de garde, but I have to admit I expected more of it.

Bottle. Hazy, dark orange with a thick white head. Green, floral and hoppy aroma with notes of cascade hops, caramel malt, citrus fruits. A balanced flavor; starts with caramel malt, cascade, citrus fruits and ends with bitter hops and fruits. In a nutshell: Nicely balanced IPA, strong on the malty side with nice bitterness and floral notes.
UPDATED: MAR 14, 2008

Bottle, 35,5cl. Hazy light orange, almost no head. Flowery green aroma with notes of citrus fruits and caramel malt. Taste is a bit more citrusy than the aroma, but otherwise pretty much what you would expect from an APA; flowery, sweet malty and hoppy with a long, bitter aftertaste. Medium bodied with lots of carbonation. A great, refreshing brew for those hot summer days.

Bottle, 50cl. Very dark brown/red with a quickly disappearing head. Sweet, roasted, malty aroma of chocolate, coffee and spices. Full-bodied, low carbonated mouthfeel with a sweet taste of liquorice, vanilla, coffee, chocolate and a hoppy finish. Almost Imperial Stoutish, but yet lighter.-A touch of Pale Ale, considering the hops on this one. Tried it with nuts, as advised by the brewery and it was a heavenly combination. I suggest everyone to try it.
UPDATED: MAR 12, 2008
UPDATED: FEB 13, 2008

Bottle #24259, 2006. Pours deep red/brown, with no head. Wonderful sweet aroma with caramel, dark fruits. Almost no carbonation, oily and warm mouthfeel with an overall sweet, bitter flavor with notes of caramel, toffee, dark syrup and fruits. Just an overly wonderful barley wine. I can only imagine how it would be when aged for 25 years.
UPDATED: FEB 8, 2008

Pours a deep red/brown color, with a tan head. A fresh, fruity and spicy aroma with notes of coffee, chocolate and their secret ingredient (heh-heh).  Quite crispy mouthfeel, with a long lasting, roasted stout-like aftertaste of chocolate and licorice. Although not the best, Nissemor is still a great brew for those cold winter days, when sitting on the sofa with a blanket wrapped around you.

Bottle. Very dark brown, with no head. Sweet, very malty, dark sugar and dark fruity aroma. A very rich, creamy and smooth mouthfeel. Sweet, very roasted and coffeish flavor. A very enjoyable beer, good all-around. Comparable to Weltenburger Asam-Bock.
